{"type":"message","id":"5490592d","parentId":"5b75e519","timestamp":"2026-05-10T13:26:02.356Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is frustrated because the `[Tokens: ... | Cache: ... | RTK: ...]` footer that appears at the end of every message, and the `🧑🏼‍💻` at the end - they're saying they already set this format and the rules, but somehow it's getting lost or not applied correctly.\n\nThey're saying \"session ท้ายข้อความ กูตั้งไปแล้วแล้วกูก็ตั้งกฎไปแล้วกูไม่เข้าใจมันหายไปได้ยังไง\" - meaning they had session retention settings and rules set up, and they're confused about how it got lost.\n \nLooking back at the MEMORY.md, the actual rule specifies keeping only 2 sessions rolling - the most recent one plus one backup before deleting the oldest. But that's being applied at the session creation level, not preservation. The real issue is probably that when Hermes restarts due to an OOM kill, the session state gets wiped even though the rules should have prevented this from happening. The session history endpoint requires a session key parameter, but I can't list what's actually stored—I can only see what's in the sessions_list. The memory notes mention a backup file at `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json.working-backup`, though that's configuration rather than conversation history. The user's frustration suggests something changed recently, possibly after that Hermes restart, so the session they're referring to might be one that was lost during that event. Looking at the session retention rules, I think the issue is that when a new session gets created after a restart, the system isn't properly maintaining the previous session's state. The user has `session-summary.md` as their current reference, but it seems like the automatic session management isn't following the rolling 2-session rule they specified. The real problem is likely that when Hermes crashes or restarts, it doesn't preserve the full conversation history that the user expects to be maintained. Looking at the session metadata, I can see the transcript is actually saved at that JSONL file path, which suggests the conversation wasn't lost but rather the display or session list got out of sync—possibly during the restart or when the session summary was being regenerated. The core issue seems to be a mismatch between what the user expects to see in their conversation history and what's actually being shown, likely stemming from the restart process or how the summary is being rebuilt.","thinkingSignature":"02dfc671ccaa1121042972245085a861ca73d52bcc6dac30a8d134afb961f3a8"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_e15qh6swum7z_1","name":"memory_search","arguments":{"query":"session retention rolling sessions rules"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":203,"output":545,"cacheRead":26495,"cacheWrite":1903,"totalTokens":29146,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778419543044,"responseId":"064fba5845ad5425efa385a269135244"}}
